metadata.name: Ripple / Cymatic #129
metadata.description:
Mathematical animations inspired by cymatics.  

Symmetric waves ripple around a boundary, causing infinitely complex patterns that evolve forever but never repeat.

Variations are the frequencies and amplitudes of waves, the boundary shape, and the velocity of phase shifts.

Some are contained, others escape to infinity.

metadata.name: Pegs In Motion #347
metadata.description:
Pegs In Motion adds a twist to the original PEGS project by adding animation, rotating the pegs to make the string loop around the grid and bring the artwork alive. Forever limited to 500 unique editions on the Tezos blockchain.

Taking inspiration from work by Karl Gerstner, Armin Hofmann, Nick Kuder and Dmitri Cherniak, Pegs In Motion explores the limits of constrained algorithmic variation. Based on the simple, playful idea of wrapping a string across a board of pegs, it shows how endless possibilities can be achieved with just a basic set of rules and a few primary colors. When done right, generative art challenges us to answer fundamental questions around creativity, beauty, and life itself.

metadata.name: Sea of Shapes #107
metadata.description:
This program was inspired by the 2022 Genuary prompt "Make a sea of shapes." It is an abstract and geometric representation of water and waves. I tried to capture the many different possible states of a sea (windy, breezy, calm etc.) by changing parameters within the program for different outputs.

Press 'p' while on Live View to save a high quality (4000x4000) png of the canvas.

Created using p5.js

Licensed under CC BY-NC 4.0

metadata.name: Ornithic #55
metadata.description:
Pure p5.js code. No svg, no image, no other materials. Creating code arts with polar coordinate system and algorithms are my passion. This generative art contains a lot of features that may be rare than common.  

• 30 color palettes // 2 of them have 3 different colors
• 4 grass structures // With the same algorithm 
• 16 flower types //  Count, leaf number and size
• 6 color functions // Different colorizations with b&w 

Also, the outputs of the project are very high resolution to print or something like that.
April / 2022
Rhaegar

metadata.name: Omega Point #100
metadata.description:
In the collapsing universe approaching singularity, the last remaining cybernetic organisms encounter the state of infinite knowledge, information, and computational resources.
Although the living creatures in the Omega Point are destined for imminent destruction, they experience infinite life.

----

Live mode controls:
'r' - change resolution
's' - save PNG
'space' - improve image quality
'f' - increase rendering speed

The image quality gradually improves over time, up to a certain level. To reach the maximum quality, press 'space'.
The rendering speed is reduced by default - press 'f' for the maximum speed.

Rendering may be GPU intensive.
Requires WebGL2.

metadata.name: Fronteras en abstracto #195
metadata.description:
A place in the abstract, walking in one direction without knowing if you will reach that place. Then, in case you find it, go to the other side before dawn.

It's just a game of words and phrases that have to be given meaning, and we find it on the frontier of something that we don't know what it is.

//

Un lugar en abstracto, caminando en una dirección sin saber si se llega a ese lugar. Luego, en caso de encontrarlo, pasar al otro lado antes del amanecer.

Es solo un juego de palabras y frases a las cuales hay que darles sentido, y lo encontramos en la frontera de algo que no sabemos qué es.

//


Keys

[s] -> download still image (in live view)
[1,2,3,4] Pixel ratios

metadata.name: Perpetual Oscillations  #64
metadata.description:
Planes expand and contract over time in different rhythms. 

Display notes:
The work is intended to be viewed running live in the browser, and there is no set aspect ratio. The viewer is invited to explore the space and choose their viewpoint. 

Controls:
Left-clicking and dragging - rotate around the center 
right-clicking and dragging - pan around the space 
Scrolling - zoom in and out 
Press b - b-side 
Press o - go back to the origin 
Press 1 to 3 - change the pixel density
Adjusting pixel density or changing the screen size will bring you back to the origin. 

License: CC BY-NC-ND 4.0

Made with p5.js

metadata.name: Whisper #365
metadata.description:
Abstract forms built with noise and texture

-------------

A note on rendering times: *Whisper has a lot going on*. It can take up to 1-5 minutes to fully render, depending on your hardware configuration, including a 15sec-1min loading phase during which lots of calculations take place (but no visuals). It'll get there, just be patient! A small loading bar along the bottom also shows the progression of the render during the drawing phase.

Press 'S' or click "Save image" to save a PNG version of the artwork while in full-screen/IPFS view

Customisation
-------------

The following parameters can be adjusted in full-screen mode.
Open the token in full-screen/IPFS mode, and add any of these to the URL:

&size=2000 (replace 2000 with any value up to around 8000) - this sets the resolution/width of the canvas in pixels. Use this to generate very large PNG images (50MB+) suitable for printing at large DPI & canvas sizes. The max value here is dependent on your hardware, might not work on mobiles etc.

&ratio=1.4 (any value between 1 and 2, default = 1.4) - set the aspect ratio of the work. By default Whisper renders at 1:1.4 but you can change this to match other printing formats. Different ratios will produce slightly different outputs, but the overall character of the artwork should still be present. Landscape mode is not supported.
